Implement download data but not save data
commitResults.messageBody:
DukeBot CLI does not read or store data locally, persisting data for
only as long as it the program is running.

By not saving data, the DukeBot cannot be used across different
sessions.

Add a way to read data in from a text file.

This commit is incomplete in that it does not include a way to write
data to a text file.

The ability to write to a file requires us to store the Tasks completion
status, something that needs to be further planned out to utilise
existing code.

commitResults.messageTitle: Persist the task list in memory and load from memory on start-up
commitResults.messageBody:
DukeBot runs with the Task List in RAM and does not persist it beyond
each session.

Temporary memory prevents the task list from being useful to a user
beyond a single session, requiring the user to keep DukeBot running.

Updates DukeBot to store the contents of its taskList to a file in
memory, allowing information to be persisted across multiple sessions.

There are some remaining To Do's involving refactoring the IO code into
separate functions and updating the Java Docs.

commitResults.messageTitle: Use LocalDate objects to store the /at and /by string
commitResults.messageBody:
Task subclasses Event and Deadline treat the /at and /by, respectively,
as Strings only, preventing any datetime manipulation or behaviour.

The /at and /by inputs are likely to be dates and by treating them as
such future functionality such as reminders or listing all tasks for a
specific day or showing overdue tasks can be incorporated.

This commit updates the /at and /by instance variables to be stored as
LocalDate objects rather than String objects.

By using LocalDate objects we are able to perform many useful date
operations on the /at and /by instance variables.
